    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i dont get the cake thing lol what do you mean? just explain the math part again with the actual numbers or something. why does it feel like most of my money is just going to the interest instead of the actual loan?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the cake analogy is a bit abstract, so let's break it down with some actual numbers to show you exactly where your money is going. Imagine you have a loan of **$10,000** with an interest rate of **6% per year**.\n\nEvery month, you pay **$100**. Here is how the \"goblin\" (the interest) eats up your payment before you even touch the principal:\n\n1.  **Month 1**: The bank calculates interest on your full **$10,000**.\n    *   Annual interest: $10,000 × 0.06 = $600.\n    *   Monthly interest: $600 ÷ 12 = **$50**.\n    *   Your payment is **$100**.\n    *   **$50 goes to interest**, and **$50 goes to principal**.\n    *   Your balance drops from $10,000 to **$9,950**.\n\n2.  **Month 2**: The bank calculates interest on your new balance of **$9,950**.",
